:: Alexandro_5 {"position":"2500,875","size":"100,100"}
<h1>Darius and Alexander Battle</h1>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
<img src="https://museoarcheologiconapoli.it/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/1-Battaglia-di-Dario-e-Alessandro-inv.-10020.-ALBANO-scaled-1.jpg" width="500">
</td>
<td class="rightColumn">
The Alexander Mosaic, discovered in 1831 in the House of the Faun in Pompeii, is a monumental floor mosaic depicting the dramatic clash between Alexander the Great and Darius III of Persia. Measuring 313 by 582 cm and composed of over a million tiny tesserae, it was created using the refined opus vermiculatum technique. The scene shows Alexander charging from the left on his horse Bucephalus, eyes fixed on the fleeing Persian king. Darius, on his chariot, looks back in desperation as one of his commanders sacrifices himself to protect him. The battlefield is chaotic, filled with spears, fallen warriors, and vivid expressions of fear and determination. The dry tree in the background may reference the Battle of Issus (333 BCE), although elements also recall Gaugamela (331 BCE), blending symbolic moments. The mosaic captures not only military might but also emotional intensity and pathos, particularly for the defeated. It likely replicates a lost Hellenistic painting, possibly by Philoxenos of Eretria. Its placement in a lavish Pompeian home suggests admiration for Alexander‚Äôs legacy and cultural identity. Today, it remains one of the most iconic works of ancient art.

[[Continue the journey|Nilotic_Scene_0]]
</td>
</tr>
</table>


