<td class="rightColumn">
The Female Portrait (also known as Matrona Pompeiana) is a Roman mosaic from the 1st century AD, discovered in the tablinum of a Pompeian house (VI, 15, 14). It depicts a noblewoman in a highly realistic style, crafted in the opus vermiculatum technique with fine tesserae. The woman is portrayed with dark hair tied in a simple aristocratic style and adorned with elegant jewelry, such as pearl and gold earrings shaped like amphorae. Her facial features are asymmetrical and individualistic, avoiding idealization. Some scholars believe the asymmetry might represent different stages of her life, though it's more likely due to variations in tesserae. The portrait reflects her high social rank, traditional Roman virtues, and conservative demeanor. It also serves as a rare precursor to the Fayyum mummy portraits.

