<p align="center">The House of the Faun is one of the largest and most luxurious private residences in ancient Pompeii, dating back to the 2nd century BCE. It covers nearly 3,000 square meters and occupies an entire city block. Named after a bronze statue of a dancing faun found in its impluvium, the house reflects the wealth and sophistication of its owner. It features elaborate mosaics, including the famous Alexander Mosaic, depicting the battle between Alexander the Great and Darius III. The layout includes multiple atriums, peristyles, and reception rooms, showcasing Hellenistic influence in Roman domestic architecture. The house also had private baths and service quarters. Its size and decoration indicate elite social status and cultural aspirations. The House of the Faun was buried during the eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 CE and rediscovered in the 19th century. Today, it stands as a key example of Roman urban domestic life and artistic achievement.</p>
