The Marine Fauna mosaic, dated to the late 2nd century BC, was found in the triclinium of the House of the Faun in Pompeii. Created in the opus vermiculatum style, it features a detailed depiction of Mediterranean marine life within a lavish decorative frame. At the center, a humorous yet dramatic fight between an octopus and a lobster unfolds. Surrounding them are meticulously rendered fish, mollusks, and crustaceans‚Äîmany of which are still familiar today. The scene is framed by rocky seascapes and includes a bird, likely a kingfisher, ready to strike. Scholars suggest the mosaic may derive from an Alexandrian painting influenced by scientific fishing texts like the Halieutica. The central animal duel also echoes Aristotle‚Äôs Historia animalium. The mosaic might reflect elite Roman taste for marine delicacies, as supported by classical literary sources.

