The Street Musicians mosaic, dated to the 2nd‚Äì1st century BC, was discovered in the so-called Villa of Cicero near Pompeii. It is a finely executed opus vermiculatum emblem depicting four figures in a lively procession, likely approaching a house. Three of the figures wear theatrical masks from New Comedy: a tambourine player (the parasitos), a cymbalist (the kolax), and a female flute player (an etaira). They are followed by a child or dwarf playing a horn, possibly collecting offerings. The scene may represent the Metragyrtai, mendicant priests of Cybele, reflecting Hellenistic theatrical and religious traditions. The composition likely draws from a lost Hellenistic painting, with one later and lower-quality replica found in Stabiae. Signed in Greek by Dioskourides of Samos, it is one of the only signed mosaics in Campania. The mosaic's delicate tonal range and spatial depth reveal exceptional artistic skill.

