The mosaic, found in the House of the Faun in Pompeii, once marked the threshold of the exedra housing the famous ‚ÄúAlexander Mosaic.‚Äù Framed by two red columns imitating Egyptian porphyry, a purple border encloses a Nile view: ducks swim in the river, a mongoose faces a cobra, a hippopotamus meets a crocodile, and a pair of ibis stand on the banks. To the left are more ducks, a small bird, and a frog on a floating leaf; to the right, other ducks and aquatic plants. All shadows fall to the right, indicating natural light from the southwest.

These ‚ÄúNilotic mosaics‚Äù trace back to Alexandrian art of the 16th century B.C., when the sacred Nile‚Äîoverseen by Elephantine priests‚Äîwas depicted with its exotic flora and fauna, linking central Africa to the Mediterranean. Ptolemy II‚Äôs 280 B.C. expedition and Rome‚Äôs conquest of Egypt in 30 B.C. spread such imagery (e.g., Palestrina‚Äôs ‚ÄúNile Mosaic‚Äù). Placing a Nilotic scene at the entrance to the Alexander Mosaic was fitting: under Isis-Tyche-Fortuna‚Äôs protection, the Nile was believed to ensure Alexander‚Äôs victory over Darius III. The three pairs of fighting animals allude to this clash, while the ibis‚Äô crossed beaks may hint at an amorous encounter rather than combat.
    
