</td>
<td class="rightColumn">
The School of Plato mosaic, dating from the mid-1st century BCE, was discovered in Pompeii at the Villa of T. Siminius Stephanus. It depicts seven bearded men, likely the "Seven Sages," wearing traditional Greek himations, seated or standing in scholarly discussion under a large tree‚Äîpossibly a plane tree. Central to the composition is a celestial sphere (an armillary sphere), symbolizing astronomical inquiry, perhaps attributed to Eratosthenes. One figure, possibly Plato, points to the sphere while others hold papyrus scrolls, suggesting a debate on cosmology or mathematics. A sundial, bronze vessels, and architectural elements frame the setting, alluding to sacred or philosophical themes. The scene may take place in Plato‚Äôs Academy in Athens, indicated by the landscape and fortified citadel in the background. Decorative garlands with masks surround the mosaic, linking intellectual pursuit with Dionysian motifs. Scholars have proposed identifications of figures as Plato, Aristotle, and Lysias based on gestures and attributes. 

