<td class="rightColumn">
This exquisite Roman mosaic, titled Meeting with the sorceress, was created using the opus vermiculatum technique with tesserae less than 1 mm in size. It depicts a theatrical scene: two young women consult an old, cross-eyed witch who holds a silver cup, likely containing love potions. All three women wear theatrical masks and are seated around a lion-footed table, surrounded by ritual objects, suggesting a magical rite. The composition imitates a stage, with steps in front and painted panels behind, drawing inspiration from Greek New Comedy. The mosaic is signed by the renowned artist Dioskourides of Samos, whose name appears in Greek at the top. It was found in the luxurious ‚ÄúVilla of Cicero‚Äù in Pompeii and is now housed in the National Archaeological Museum of Naples.

